{"runId":"qwen-qwen3.6-35b-a3b@2026-05-13T21-11-24-684Z","slug":"one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams","locale":"it","model":"qwen/qwen3.6-35b-a3b","modelPath":"qwen-qwen3.6-35b-a3b","createdAt":"2026-05-13T21:13:31.446Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/it/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/it/qwen-qwen3.6-35b-a3b/2026-05-13T21-11-24-684Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5e23bd6661ed61df952a39bf65d61ca0a0d01f23e047cdf168f7bbdac407baeb","outputHash":"326ebdfeda25e68df3019bf26197652d7165aac81e6c0f6187be5ede92b6a413","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"This pragmatic technical guide argues that engineering teams should default to simple Key-Value (KV) stores like Redis, S3, or DynamoDB when prototyping new features, rather than immediately adopting SQL or MongoDB. By adopting a \"thinking in keys\" mindset, developers can rapidly model hierarchical and graph-like data, avoid costly schema migration churn, and leverage highly optimized lookups during early development. Targeted at mid-to-senior software engineers and system architects, the article maintains an analytical yet conversational tone, framing KV stores as a strategic, low-friction starting point that simplifies later migration to relational databases. Ultimately, the author contends that starting simple forces more intentional data modeling, resulting in higher-quality SQL designs once complex querying or JOINs become necessary.","totalInputTokens":6303,"totalOutputTokens":21723,"totalCacheReadTokens":0,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":96554,"totalCostUsd":0.022668449999999996,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"qwen/qwen3.6-35b-a3b","chunkSize":"10p","totalChunks":5,"totalInputTokens":6303,"totalOutputTokens":21