{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-14T02-03-47-850Z","slug":"one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams","locale":"he","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-14T02:03:56.069Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/he/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/he/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-14T02-03-47-850Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5e23bd6661ed61df952a39bf65d61ca0a0d01f23e047cdf168f7bbdac407baeb","outputHash":"b786f345acd69af9da333cbd232ed0804d907d482e9e01866aff2daf3a09d3db","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that feature teams should begin new services with the simplest possible persistence—typically a key‑value (KV) store such as Redis, DynamoDB, or S3—rather than defaulting to relational or document databases. It explains how to “think in keys,” showing concrete key naming conventions and how KV patterns can model hierarchies, graphs, and trees, while also listing clear criteria for when KV is appropriate (massive scale, primary‑key access, simple or hierarchical data) and when to avoid it (property searches, joins, complex constraints). The tone is a practical tutorial mixed with anecdotal persuasion, using the recurring metaphor of “building on keys” and framing KV as a cheap, fast foundation that can later be migrated to richer stores if needed. The intended audience is software engineers and engineering managers responsible for designing data layers for new features or services.","totalInputTokens":6694,"totalOutputTokens":2715,"totalCacheReadTokens":0,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":6911,"totalCostUsd":0.000749766,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-estimate","telemetry":{"model":"openai/gpt-oss-120