{"runId":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro@2026-05-14T02-03-53-681Z","slug":"one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams","locale":"ar","model":"openai/gpt-oss-120b:nitro","modelPath":"openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro","createdAt":"2026-05-14T02:04:01.822Z","sourcePath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/index.mdx","targetPath":"src/content/posts/2024-09-29--one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/ar/index.mdx","candidatePath":"reports/i18n/one-weird-trick-to-speed-up-feature-teams/ar/openai-gpt-oss-120b-nitro/2026-05-14T02-03-53-681Z/candidate.mdx","sourceHash":"5e23bd6661ed61df952a39bf65d61ca0a0d01f23e047cdf168f7bbdac407baeb","outputHash":"bb9caa3403ed2789692e1e4b7fc27fe22ab6cd8a4abf521ba1fb2a40dd9438ae","reasoningEffort":"low","temperature":0.3,"maxTokens":16000,"timeoutMs":200000,"articleSummary":"**Summary**  \nThe article argues that feature teams should start new services with the simplest possible persistence—a key‑value (KV) store such as Redis, DynamoDB, or S3—rather than defaulting to relational or document databases. It explains how virtually any domain model can be expressed as hierarchical keys (e.g., `user/123/friends`), showing that KV patterns naturally encode graphs and trees, speed early development, and reduce schema‑migration overhead. The piece outlines when KV is appropriate (massive scale, key‑based lookups, simple or hierarchical data) and when to avoid it (search by properties, joins, complex constraints), and notes that migrating from KV to SQL is usually easier than the reverse. The tone is a practical tutorial mixed with anecdotal advocacy, using the recurring metaphor of “thinking in keys” to frame the design shift. Intended for software engineers, architects, and product teams who design data layers for new features.","totalInputTokens":6720,"totalOutputTokens":2473,"totalCacheReadTokens":2816,"totalCacheWriteTokens":0,"totalDurationMs":7151,"totalCostUsd":0.0007072199999999999,"pricingSource":"local-openrouter-